    "analysis": "We computed global thresholds (p95/p5) for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) of the five candidate services using the full series, then filtered metric points to the incident window (2024-01-24T09:34:39+00:00 through 2024-01-24T10:04:39+00:00). Anomaly detection (value >= p95 OR value <= p5) highlights two primary faulty services: ts-travel-service (multiple KPIs with anomalies; most first anomalies ~2024-01-24T09:37:00Z) and ts-auth-service (several resource KPIs with anomalies; first anomalies around 09:37–09:47Z). Trace aggregation for the same window shows heavy trace traffic involving ts-travel-service (trace.to_/from_ts-travel-service with many rows) and fewer but present traces for ts-auth-service (trace.to_ts-auth-service with 50 rows). Traces show travel-service appears in many call paths (high volume) and auth-service has moderate volume. According to the diagnosis workflow, we must now verify which KPI anomalies constitute real faults (consecutive anomalous sub-series) and their start times to localize the root cause. Specifically, we should examine consecutive anomaly sequences (not isolated spikes) for the most suspicious KPIs of ts-travel-service and ts-auth-service to determine the earliest fault occurrence and severity before using traces/logs for final localization.",
